<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<worksheet xml:id="fun2-sample" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>FUN-2 Sample Outcomes</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>For the quiz on this outcome you would be given 50 minutes to complete 4 problems. Here are samples 
      of the types of problems you will encounter:</p>
  </introduction>
  
  <page>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>Give the equation for the line passing through the point 
          (4,-1,5) and in the direction orthogonal to the plane 
        with equation <m>2x-5y+z=1</m>. Give the parametric, symmetric, 
      and vector equations.</p>
      </statement>
      <hint><p>To find the equation of a line in 3D space, you 
        need a point on the line and a direction vector. The 
        direction vector should be orthogonal to the given plane.</p></hint>
      <answer><p>Parametric: <m>\vec{r}(t) = \lt 4, -1, 5 \gt + t \lt 2, -5, 1 \gt</m></p>
      <p>Symmetric: <m>\frac{x-4}{2} = \frac{y+1}{-5} = \frac{z-5}{1}</m></p>
      <p>Vector: <m>\vec{v}(t) = \lt 4+2t, -1-5t, 5+t \gt</m></p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>First, we find the normal vector to the plane <m>2x-5y+z=1</m>, which is <m>\vec{n} = \lt 2, -5, 1 \gt</m>. This vector is orthogonal to the plane and can be used as the direction vector for the line.</p>
        <p>Using the point (4, -1, 5) and the direction vector <m>\vec{d} = \lt 2, -5, 1 \gt</m>, we can write the parametric equations as:</p>
        <p><m>x = 4 + 2t</m>, <m>y = -1 - 5t</m>, <m>z = 5 + t</m></p>
        <p>The symmetric equations are:</p>
        <p><m>\frac{x-4}{2} = \frac{y+1}{-5} = \frac{z-5}{1}</m></p>
        <p>The vector equation is:</p>
        <p><m>\vec{r}(t) = \lt 4, -1, 5 \gt + t \lt 2, -5, 1 \gt</m></p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>Find the equation of the plane that passes through the 
          points (2,0,4), (1,3,5), and (2,-1,0).</p>
        </statement>
       <hint><p>To find the equation of a plane through three points, 
        you can use the cross product of two vectors formed by the 
        points to find the normal vector.</p></hint>
        <answer><p>Plane: <m>11x+4y-z=18</m></p></answer>
        <solution><p>We first find two vectors in the plane:</p>
        <p><m>\vec{u} = (1,3,5) - (2,0,4) = \lt -1,3,1 \gt</m></p>
        <p><m>\vec{v} = (2,-1,0) - (2,0,4) = \lt 0,-1,-4 \gt</m></p>
        <p>The normal vector is:</p>
        <p><m>\vec{n} = \vec{u} \times \vec{v} = \lt 3(-4) - 1(-1), 1(0) - (-1)(-4), (-1)(-1) - 3(0) \gt = \lt -12 + 1, 0 - 4, 1 - 0 \gt = \lt -11, -4, 1 \gt</m></p>
        <p>The equation of the plane is:</p>
        <p><m>-11(x-2) - 4(y-0) + 1(z-4) = 0</m></p>
        <p>Simplifying:</p>
        <p><m>-11x + 22 - 4y + z - 4 = 0</m></p>
        <p><m>11x + 4y - z = 18</m></p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <introduction><p>A plane is given by the equation 3x-2y+x=4.</p></introduction>
        <task>
          <statement><p>Find the equation of a plane parallel to the given plane that 
            passes through the point (-2,5,3).</p></statement>
          <hint><p>Parallel planes have the same normal vector.</p></hint>
          <answer><p><m>3x-2y+z=-13</m></p></answer>
          <solution><p>The normal vector to the given plane is 
            <m>\vec{n} = \lt 3, -2, 1 \gt</m>. Since the new plane is 
            parallel to the given plane, it has the same normal vector. Using the point 
            (-2,5,3) and the normal vector <m>\vec{n} = \lt 3, -2, 1 \gt</m>, the 
            equation of the new plane is:</p>
          <p><m>3(x-(-2)) - 2(y-5) + 1(z-3) = 0</m></p>
          <p>Simplifying:</p>
          <p><m>3x + 6 - 2y + 10 + z - 3 = 0</m></p>
          <p><m>3x - 2y + z + 13 = 0</m></p>
          <p>Therefore, the equation of the new plane is:</p>
          <p><m>3x - 2y + z = -13</m></p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement><p> Find the angle between the given plane 
          and the xy-coordinate plane. Give an exact simplified 
        answer.</p></statement>
        <hint><p>To find the angle between two planes, you can 
          use the dot product of their normal vectors.</p></hint>
          <answer><p><m>\theta=cos^{-1}\left(\frac{\sqrt{14}}{14}\right)</m></p></answer>
          <solution><p>The normal vector to the given plane is 
            <m>\vec{n_1} = \lt 3, -2, 1 \gt</m>. The normal vector 
            to the xy-coordinate plane is <m>\vec{n_2} = \lt 0, 0, 1 \gt</m>. 
            The angle between the planes is:</p>
          <p><m>\cos(\theta) = \frac{\vec{n_1} \cdot \vec{n_2}}{|\vec{n_1}||\vec{n_2}|} = 
            \frac{1}{\sqrt{14} \cdot 1} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{14}}</m></p>
          <p>Therefore, <m>\theta = \cos^{-1}\left(\frac{1}{\sqrt{14}}\right) = 
            \cos^{-1}\left(\frac{\sqrt{14}}{14}\right)</m></p>
        </solution>
        </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>Identify the surface given by <m>z=16-x^2-y^2</m></p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
      <image xml:id="Elliptic_Paraboloid" width="80%" source="Elliptic_Paraboloid.png"/>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>The equation <m>z=16-x^2-y^2</m> can be rewritten as 
          <m>x^2+y^2+z=16</m>. This is the equation of an 
          elliptic paraboloid opening downward with vertex at 
          (0,0,16).</p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>Identify the surface given by <m>y^2+9z^2=9</m></p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
      <figure>
        <caption>Elliptic Cylinder</caption>
        <image xml:id="Elliptic_Cylinder" width="80%" source="Elliptic_Cylinder.png"/>
      </figure></answer>
      <solution>
        <p>The equation <m>y^2+9z^2=9</m> can be rewritten as 
          <m>\frac{y^2}{9}+\frac{z^2}{1}=1</m>. This is the equation of an 
          elliptic cylinder opening along the x-axis with semi-axes of length 3 and 1.</p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <introduction><p>Given <m> 4x^2-y^2+z^2-8x+2y+2z+3=0</m>.</p></introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
        <p>Rewrite the equation in standard form.</p>
        </statement>
        <hint><p>To find the standard form, complete the square 
          for each variable, then simplify the equation.</p></hint>
        <answer><p><m>4(x-1)^2-(y-1)^2+(z+1)^2=1</m></p></answer>
        <solution>
          <p>First we can get the like variables together:</p>
          <p><m>4x^2-8x-y^2+2y+z^2+2z+3=0</m></p>
          <p>We then need to factor out the leading coefficient 
            for each set of variables: <m>4(x^2-2x)- (y^2-2y)+(z^2+2z)+3=0</m></p>
          <p>Completing the square for each variable, we add the constants:</p>
          <p><m>4(x^2-2x+1)- (y^2-2y+1)+(z^2+2z+1)=-3+4-1+1</m></p>
          <p> Then we can rewrite the equation as:</p>
          <p><m>4(x-1)^2-(y-1)^2+(z+1)^2=1</m></p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
        <p>Identify the surface and the axis.</p>
        </statement>
        <answer><p>This is a hyperbolic paraboloid with the axis 
          along the y-axis.</p></answer>
      </task>
    </exercise>
  </page>
</worksheet>
